"credit":"Photograph: Keystone/Getty Images","photographer":"Keystone","source":"Getty Images","width":"500","height":"300","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/e3da9113335ca3c16795731c64ec3bc0b5172df5/0_352_2964_1778/500.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"e3da9113335ca3c16795731c64ec3bc0b5172df5","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"95g33/huch/1450/hw0280","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/e3da9113335ca3c16795731c64ec3bc0b5172df5","picdarUrn":"GD*20401253"}}]}],"references":[],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true","subscriptionDatabases":"false","developerCommunity":"false"},"section":{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","editions":[{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},{"id":"books/booksblog/2016/aug/18/books-to-give-you-hope-station-eleven-by-emily-st-john-mandel","type":"article","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-18T07:00:26Z","webTitle":"Books to give you hope: Station Eleven by Emily St John Mandel","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/aug/18/books-to-give-you-hope-station-eleven-by-emily-st-john-mandel","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksblog/2016/aug/18/books-to-give-you-hope-station-eleven-by-emily-st-john-mandel","fields":{"headline":"Books to give you hope: Station Eleven by Emily St John Mandel","standfirst":"<p>I hate apocalyptic fiction. But this tale of the end of a civilisation shows how even in the ruins, humanity can preserve its virtues </p><ul><li><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/aug/10/books-to-give-you-hope-gilead-by-marilynne-robinson\">Why we’re writing about books to give you hope this summer</a><br></li></ul>","trailText":"I hate apocalyptic fiction. But this tale of the end of a civilisation shows how even in the ruins, humanity can preserve its virtues ","byline":"David Barnett","body":"<p>There ain’t a lot of hope at the end of the world. And I really, really hate apocalyptic fiction. So my choice for the books to give you hope series? Emily St John Mandel’s Station Eleven: a book about the end of the world.</p> <p>When Station Eleven was first published almost two years ago, I read the press release, flipped through it and put it on my pile of books I’ll probably never get round to. I didn’t need another dose of post-apocalyptic bleakness in my life.</p> <p>I really do hate this kind of fiction. I’m the man who’s never seen The Walking Dead and has no intention of ever doing so. The end of the world just isn’t for me. Why would it be? It’s an awful, awful place. I don’t want to immerse myself in a world where civilisation has reverted to barbarity, where every day is a grinding battle just to survive until the next day, when it all begins again. What is there to enjoy in a ruined world where people fight over water and food? Where it’s kill or be killed? Where women seem to be routinely reduced to commodities to join the list of scarce resources to be scrapped over?</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/sep/22/station-eleven-review-emily-st-john-mandel-haunting-dystopian-vision\">Station Eleven review – Emily St John Mandel’s haunting dystopian vision</a> </p> </aside>  <p>But I kept picking it up again, and flipping through, even as Mandel’s “incomplete list” of things that the post-ruin world has lost forever chilled and depressed me:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>No more diving into pools of chlorinated water.</p> <p>No more porch lights with moths fluttering on summer nights.</p> <p>No more trains running under the surface of cities.</p> <p>No more cities …</p> </blockquote> <p>I must have been feeling particularly bleak one day, because I sat down to read it. And I was captivated.</p> <p>Station Eleven’s apocalypse is wrought by the Georgia Flu, a virulent disease that races across the planet, kills within hours and wipes out 99% of the world’s population. Mandel switches between the day the pandemic hits her native Canada and the world 20 years later. </p> <p>And while the ground zero stuff is as terrifying and horrible as you’d expect, the revelation comes in the chapters set two decades after the supposed end of the world. Because it hasn’t ended at all.</p> <p>It’s not the world we know, or would want to. It’s a mess, it’s lawless, it’s chaotic and it’s brutal. But, as I ripped through the book, I realised it was offering what other apocalyptic fiction never seemed to even bother with.</p> <p>Hope.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>While survival is vital, it isn’t enough. We must live as well as survive, because otherwise what’s the point?</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>And not just hope that eventually we’d rebuild and repair and jump-start society all over again. Station Eleven offers a different type of hope – that amid the horror of collapse, humanity doesn’t always have to revert to savagery.</p> <p>The 20-years-later chapters focus on an itinerant group of actors and performers called the Travelling Symphony who move around the rudimentary settlements built in the ruins of Canada and the northernmost tip of the US, bringing Shakespeare to the survivors. Offering them not just a glimpse of how things were, but – crucially – how things can be again.</p> <p>But not in terms of subway trains and swimming pools and “towns glimpsed from the sky through airplane windows”; instead how art and beauty can not only survive, but thrive. And through them, so can we.</p> <p>The caravan of the Travelling Symphony has a quote from Star Trek incongruously painted on the side (though many of the players are too young to even remember the pre-Georgia Flu world): “<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Survival_Instinct_(Star_Trek:_Voyager)\">Survival Is Insufficient</a>.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/audio/2014/oct/10/books-podcast-literary-dystopia-fiction\">Literary dystopias with Emily St John Mandel and Clemens J Setz – podcast</a> </p> </aside>  <p>That’s not to say that there aren’t horrors and thrills in Mandel’s apocalypse. The chaotic first year after the Flu strikes is alluded to in dark tones, but never explored too deeply, and there are brigands and mad prophets aplenty; this is no pastoral idyll of a future world.</p> <p>Yet the strength of the novel is that it doesn’t concentrate on mere survival. That is taken as read. But as the wisdom of Star Trek teaches, survival is vital, but it isn’t enough. We must live as well as survive, because otherwise what’s the point?</p> <p>I still hate apocalyptic fiction. But I love Station Eleven, and if I have to live through the end of the world – God forbid! – I really hope Mandel is writing it.</p>","wordcount":"728","commentCloseDate":"2016-08-21T07:00:26Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4qey2","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/b9e3a0c2e712ae4dade45b5b7f81a25bb7eb260e/130_1702_1519_911/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/series/books-to-give-you-hope","type":"series","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books to give you hope","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/series/books-to-give-you-hope","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/books-to-give-you-hope","references":[],"description":"<p>During a summer of bleak news stories, Guardian writers recommend favourite books that offer the reader a bright side</p>"},{"id":"books/science-fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Science fiction","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/scie