20/500.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"SURFER ON WAIKIKI SHORES<br>A surfer makes his way back to shore after a day of surfing on Waikiki's famous surfing shores, September 15, 2003. Riding a wave of public popularity, the Hawaii Board of Education recently recommended that surfing become state-sanctioned high school sport for the first time. Although Hawaii is the birth place of the wave riding, only a few schools have surf clubs, but since they are not 'official' clubs, under present guidelines the school's name or mascot is not allowed in competition. REUTERS/Lucy Pemoni","credit":"Photograph: Lucy Pemoni/REUTERS","photographer":"Lucy Pemoni","source":"REUTERS","width":"500","height":"300","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/2fa02667e41afb556d46b4794bb2c471b5479592/0_4_2200_1320/500.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"2fa02667e41afb556d46b4794bb2c471b5479592","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"WAI01D","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/2fa02667e41afb556d46b4794bb2c471b5479592","picdarUrn":"PD*3841274"}}]}],"references":[],"rights":{"syndicatable":"false","subscriptionDatabases":"false","developerCommunity":"false"},"section":{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","editions":[{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},{"id":"books/2016/aug/17/shame-and-wonder-by-david-searcy-review","type":"article","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-17T14:30:06Z","webTitle":"Shame and Wonder by David Searcy review – essays on the oddness of the world","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/17/shame-and-wonder-by-david-searcy-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/17/shame-and-wonder-by-david-searcy-review","fields":{"headline":"Shame and Wonder by David Searcy review – essays on the oddness of the world","standfirst":"From dental floss to breakfast cereal to space travel – compelling musings from the latest in a long line of outsider American essayists","trailText":"From dental floss to breakfast cereal to space travel – compelling musings from the latest in a long line of outsider American essayists","byline":"Brian Dillon","body":"<p>The first essay in David Searcy’s strange, lucid, sometimes frustrating collection finds him at the dentist in his native Dallas, thinking about revenge. The hygienist tells him that her father once lured a lamb-worrying coyote to its death using a recording of her infant sister crying. It’s a sufficiently curious tale for Searcy to take the father’s number; but for obscure reasons he delays contacting the resourceful rancher for a year. Meanwhile the essay meanders about until Searcy makes up his mind, touching on the author’s bad attitude towards dental floss, his encounters with giant turtles and toads, the <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/technology/google-maps\" title=\"\">Google Maps</a> view of the ranch he has failed to visit. When at last he gets there he discovers the hygienist’s father also has tapes with titles such as Raccoon Fight and Grey Fox Distress. The final import of the essay is voiced by the man’s wife, who takes Searcy’s visit as a chance to ask: “Why did you let her cry?”</p> <p>The essay form, Theodor Adorno wrote in 1958, “freely associates what can be found associated in the freely chosen subject”. The 21 essays in <em>Shame and Wonder</em> take full advantage of the genre’s arbitrariness, its habit of digression and urge to reveal unlikely affinities. In “The Depths of Baseball Sadness”, Searcy considers his own digressive temperament: “What on earth do you call that? Fielder’s taken off his glove to get down on his knees and build little houses out of rocks for ants.” Searcy’s method and style consist of extreme concentration on anecdote or detail, followed by unexpected swerves of thought and phrase, taking us somewhere quite different. As a writer he resembles the friend of his youth who, he tells us, aspired to live suspended beneath a neighbour’s huge pink Cadillac: nose to the asphalt and no inkling where he is headed.</p> <p>His method appears to have its origins in his childhood in the 1950s, when he had a wide open attitude to the future, schooled on specific cultural artefacts. As a boy he persuaded his parents – quite how is mysterious – to buy him a Danish modernist armchair: “All the hard, pragmatic thrust and brace smeared out into those curves in such a graceful contradiction that knew how, exactly how, to take the weight without constraining one’s position.” It seemed that he (and by extension the US) would speed comfortably into a future imagined by his favourite TV shows, such as <em>Space Patrol</em> and <em>Tom Corbett, Space Cadet</em>. But he felt some resistance already: young Searcy’s homemade space rockets fizzled and fell over, his homemade seismograph (a jury-rigged gramophone) registered only “unlikely properties, effects oblique and subtle and evasive” – tremors from the imagination, in other words.</p> <p>His experiments may have failed but Searcy maintained an affinity with scientists. “Is science everywhere, like metaphor and tragedy?” he asks. The answer might be that, whatever else it is, science is Searcy’s best source of metaphors. He recalls that after his divorce, his daughter, alone in her new bedroom for the first time, resembled an astronomer keenly focused on her telescope, with her face pressed to the dark. Astronomy, space travel and science fiction give Searcy a sense of the oddness of the world in which he grew up and a fund of the best images to describe it. It’s hard to read his account of a mid-1950s <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/07/mickey-rooney-obituary\" title=\"\">Mickey Rooney</a> TV show, <em>The Moon or Bust</em> – in which the heroic dope thinks he has made it to the moon but is actually in a local field with a cow – and not go looking for the episode online, to marvel at the simplicity of its estrangement.</p> <p>At times Searcy’s combination of quotidian amazement and apparent nostalgia can seem banal or twee. The heart sinks when an essay begins, as “Cereal Prize” does, by musing: “I suspect a broader meaning to our breakfast cereal back in the 1950s.” And it’s permissible to wonder what a more eccentric and dogged practitioner of the essay such as Nicholson Baker would do with the topic of paper-aeroplane design. But then you realise that the first of these is about fundamental kinds of longing that are not exhausted by plastic toys in Puffed Wheat boxes, and the second concerns a childhood friend who later died in a motorcycle crash. “You can see what’s going on here, right? The unforeseen stabilities. The buoyancy. The darkness … ” The links and leaps that Searcy makes can appear too swift and even glib, the scale of the essay too easily tipped from reminiscence to revelation. But in “Cereal Prizes” the pivot is perfectly timed: it comes at the end, and unbalances the whole.</p> <p>Searcy is a novelist who has turned to the essay in his late 60s. His publishers tell us he writes his non-fiction “straight up” on notepad and typewriter, as if that were some guarantee of authenticity or commitment. I doubt Searcy himself believes such guff, but he does have a tendency to perform a certain old-guy remove from current technology: he finds <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/feb/08/google-maps-10-anniversary-iphone-android-street-view\" title=\"\">Google Maps</a> “ghostly”, and is alarmed to find himself invited online to “Fuck Sexy Girls near Dallas”. This habit of claiming to be down-home and detached is maybe one of the reasons <em>Shame and Wonder</em> arrives trailing cloudy blurbs from the likes of Leslie Jamison and John Jeremiah Sullivan. Searcy looks like the latest in a long line of outsider(ish) American essayists. It’s a redundant gambit, on his part and his handlers’, because at its best – “The Hudson River School”, the paper-plane essay, a remarkable piece about Max Fleischer cartoons – his work enacts odd connections between past, present and future, without having to telegraph their presence.</p> <p>• Brian Dillon’s <em>The Great Explosion</em> is out in paperback. To order a copy of <em>Shame and Wonder</em> by David Searcy (William Heinemann, £16.99) for £13.93 go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/shame-and-  wonder.html?utm_source=\" editoriallink&amp;amp;utm_medium=\"merch&amp;amp;utm_campaign=articl&quot;&quot;\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p.</p>","wordcount":"1021","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-30T16:38:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/5vxxv","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/c2fb3b8fc84b8fc675b536cc7f16150b49890824/77_858_1589_953/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/essays","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Essays","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/essays","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/essays","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webTitle":"Culture","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","type":"tone","webTitle":"Reviews","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tone/reviews","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tone/reviews","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/review","type":"tracking","webTitle":"UK Review","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.