’Brien review – a dark, distilled form of Englishness","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/17/once-again-assembled-here-by-sean-obrien-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/17/once-again-assembled-here-by-sean-obrien-review","fields":{"headline":"Once Again Assembled Here by Sean O’Brien review – a dark, distilled form of Englishness","standfirst":"A public school falls under the shadow of fascism in a retired teacher’s chronicle of deaths foretold","trailText":"A public school falls under the shadow of fascism in a retired teacher’s chronicle of deaths foretold","byline":"Charles Fernyhough","body":"<p>For a storyteller, the English public school is a generous gift. Like the ocean-locked ship or the medieval monastery, it presents the novelist with the kind of closed system that is ideal for testing hunches about the workings of human hearts. When traditions of how to think and behave have been established over centuries, there is a settled inevitability that things will keep on being done the way they’ve always been done. Just by turning up to lessons, you’re deepening the conspiracy.</p> <p>That’s true of the teachers as much as the pupils. In poet Sean O’Brien’s second novel, Stephen Maxwell has recently retired from an unremarkable career teaching history at Blake’s, “a church in light disguise” on the outskirts of a North Sea port. Ostensibly charged with writing the school’s official history, his leisurely obsession is reconstructing the events of 40 years earlier, when the spirit of late-60s revolution unleashed monsters that had little to do with Paris or free love. It is a chronicle of deaths foretold, opening with the cadences of a confession.</p> <p>Blake’s is the only home Stephen has ever had, its inmates his only family. Orphaned young, he is dumped there aged eight, into the care of the dependably charismatic teacher Carson. Stephen discovers girls, intellectual passions and the world beyond the school woods, and hones a talent for romance that belies his semi-monastic upbringing. Embarrassed at university by an affair with a don’s wife, Stephen finds history repeating itself when, as a young teacher returning to the fold, he starts rattling the headboard with the spouse of the school’s mysterious absent headmaster. With her “feral nobility” and age-defying good looks, Maggie is caught up, like everyone else in the novel, in the dealings of General Allingham, Yorkshire’s answer to <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/19/oswald-mosley-blackshirts-uniform-1935\" title=\"\">Oswald Mosley</a>. An old-school fascist with an eye on a by-election seat, Allingham enlists the unscrupulous energies of Charles Rackham, another denizen of the Blake’s staffroom. When Carson’s body floats to the surface of the school pond, the trail of ex-Blakeans hurrying to investigate seems to extend up to the higher echelons of government. If you get the feeling that everyone in the novel is connected to Blake’s, that’s part of the stifling recursiveness that O’Brien needs for his narrative.</p> <p>This is a bookish book. Within a few early pages, we’ve had quotes from Larkin, Eliot, Hopkins, Dante and Stevenson. Even the villain, Rackham, is defined in terms of his qualities as a poet, which in his case are a mark of irredeemable moral affliction. Characters are individuated by what they like to read, and much of the action unfolds in libraries and bookshops. Pubs make for a welcome change of scene, and the funny banter between young Stephen and his buddy Smallbone contributes to the sort of intellectual slacker feel I enjoyed in O’Brien’s previous novel <em>Afterlife</em>. The dark shadow around Stephen’s university exploits is dexterously handled, and gives the novel an emotional centre that is oddly lost amid all the killings. We are in the territory of Lindsay Anderson’s <em>if…</em>, but instead of an armed insurgence from the pupils, it is the masters who are manning the guns.</p> <p>It’s difficult to manage this mix of violence and absurdity without occasionally straying into the Pythonesque. But having almost all of the characters connected to the school means that the plot can struggle to breathe, and the control of this oddly overdetermined narrative is not always entirely assured. Stephen is a strangely emotionless protagonist, even when horrors are unfolding. The author seems to be interested in a particular distillation of Englishness: “bravery, endurance, an ironic obedience to necessary authority, a readiness to kill for the cause given half a chance”. Where a nationality crystallises as an idea, there will inevitably be people who want to defend it and impose it on others. It’s no comfort to learn from this subtle, compassionate, quietly outraged novel that English fascists in 1968 campaigned to join Europe. As Stephen traces the link between Rackham’s petty English nastiness and his wartime dealings with those who would industrialise racial hatred, he reminds us how readily the conspiracy of the institution can become a refuge for the unspeakable. If the machinery of Blake’s is inexhaustibly able to assimilate and forget, we can thank its fussy self-absorption, its isolation and what Arnold Bennett called a “grim passion for the status quo”. Which are, of course, just the conditions you need for the rivers-of-blood rhetoricians to slouch into action.</p> <p>• To order <em>Once Again Assembled Here</em> for £12.29 (RRP £14.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/once-again-assembled-here.htmlutm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","wordcount":"822","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-30T16:02:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4px6p","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/63465d248db13dafb11080