afd5458edd9934e6432646a62d9d53d9bb258f50/855_642_1145_687/500.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"afd5458edd9934e6432646a62d9d53d9bb258f50","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"HK802","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/afd5458edd9934e6432646a62d9d53d9bb258f50","picdarUrn":"PD*5675434"}}]}],"references":[],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true","subscriptionDatabases":"false","developerCommunity":"false"},"section":{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","editions":[{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},{"id":"books/2016/aug/17/gardener-and-the-carpenter-by-alison-gopnik-review","type":"article","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-17T06:30:24Z","webTitle":"The Gardener and the Carpenter by Alison Gopnik review – modern parenting is all wrong","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/17/gardener-and-the-carpenter-by-alison-gopnik-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/17/gardener-and-the-carpenter-by-alison-gopnik-review","fields":{"headline":"The Gardener and the Carpenter by Alison Gopnik review – modern parenting is all wrong","standfirst":"We worry too much and do too much for them: children flourish when they are given freedom. When it comes to looking after kids, be a gardener not a carpenter","trailText":"We worry too much and do too much for them: children flourish when they are given freedom. When it comes to looking after kids, be a gardener not a carpenter","byline":"Bee Wilson","body":"<p>In 2011, a team of psychologists did an experiment with some preschool children. The scientists gave the children a toy made of many plastic tubes, each with a different function: one squeaked, one lit up, one made music and the final tube had a hidden mirror. With half the children, an experimenter came into the room and bumped – apparently accidentally – into the tube that squeaked. “Oops!” she said. With the other children, the scientist acted more deliberately, like a teacher. “Oh look at my neat toy! Let me show you how it works,” she said while purposely pressing the beeper. The children were then left alone to play with the toy.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2000/jan/26/parents.familyandrelationships\">Tears, tantrums and other experiments</a> </p> </aside>  <p>In the “accidental” group, the children freely played with the toy in various random ways. Through experimenting, they discovered all the different functions of the tubes: the light, the music, the mirror. The other group, the children who had been deliberately taught how to use the toy by the teacher, played with it in a much more limited and repetitive way. They squeaked the beeper over and over again, never discovering all the other things the toy could do.</p> <p>For the US developmental psychologist <a href=\"http://www.alisongopnik.com/\" title=\"\">Alison Gopnik</a>, this experiment reveals some of the deep flaws in modern parenting. Parents try – heaven knows, we try – to help our children win at a succession of tasks in life, from Duplo towers to GCSEs. But in the process, Gopnik argues, we may end up limiting the very potential we are trying to foster. She excoriates the parents “who want to shape their three-year-olds into Harvard freshmen”. On Gopnik’s reading, children flourish the most – like the preschoolers in the accidental group – when they are left free to explore. They also learn as much from our mistakes as they do from our instructions. “Our job is not to shape our children’s minds; it’s to let those minds explore all the possibilities that the world allows.”</p> <p>Gopnik’s central argument in this fascinating and passionate diatribe is that modern, affluent societies approach child-rearing in a wrongheaded way. Middle-class families feel under immense pressure to parent our children in such a way that they will turn out right. We speak of good and bad parenting. We shuttle them to football practice and ballet lessons; and later, push them to complete their Duke of Edinburgh awards. We anxiously scrutinise their book bags each night, or feel guilty that we are failing to do so. We worry whether they are getting enough sleep, making enough friends. There’s a tendency to endlessly query our own choices. Are we working too much or too little? Are we protecting them too much or not enough?</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>To be a wife is not to engage in 'wifing', so why do we imagine that we can – or should – parent a child?</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>For Gopnik, these are simply the wrong questions, because we should not think of looking after children as “parenting” at all. The trouble with parenting, on her reading, is that it treats looking after children as a form of work rather than a form of love. And by treating childcare as work, parents are doomed to feel dissatisfied, because it’s a relentless, thankless, messy, unpaid occupation. But, Gopnik adds, it’s “a pretty great kind of love, at least for most of us”.</p> <p>The parenting model assumes that parents are always active and children are always passive, but Gopnik would like us to think of it as an interplay, like dancing, or like the other important relationships in our lives. “To be a wife is not to engage in ‘wifing’, to be a friend is not to ‘friend’, even on Facebook, and we don’t ‘child’ our mothers and fathers. Yet these relationships are central to who we are.” So why do we imagine that we can – or should – parent a child?</p> <p>The book’s title, <em>The Gardener and the Carpenter</em>, comes from a metaphor about the parent-child relationship. To seek to parent a child, Gopnik argues, is to behave like a carpenter, chiselling away at something to achieve a particular end-goal – in this case, a certain kind of person. A carpenter believes that he or she has the power to transform a block of wood into a chair. When we garden, on the other hand, we do not believe we are the ones who single-handedly create the cabbages or the roses. Rather, we toil to create the conditions in which plants have the best chance of flourishing. The gardener knows that plans will often be thwarted, Gopnik writes. “The poppy comes up neon orange instead of pale pink … black spot and rust and aphids can never be defeated.” If parents are like gardeners, the aim is to create a protected space in which our children can become themselves, rather than trying to mould them.</p> <p>The parenting model, Gopnik argues, has been a spectacular failure. The US, where billions of dollars are spent on parenting books, “also has the highest rates of infant mortality and child poverty in the developing world”. In both the US and the UK, the education system has become <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/feb/20/primary-school-review\" title=\"\">ever more focused on “outcomes”</a>, in the form of test scores, and yet rates of illiteracy, particularly among lower income children, remain high. Moreover, children who “don’t fit the demands of school are treated as if they were ill or defective or disabled”. Instead of obsessing about test scores, Gopnik suggests that we should as a society care for children more – particularly poor ones. She cites early years interventions: children who have <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/oct/02/nurseries-childcare-pre-school-cortisol\" title=\"\">access to high quality nurseries</a> or whose parents are given home-visit support “grow up to be healthier and have higher incomes”.</p> <p>Gopnik also insists that the narrow parenting model is based on bad science. In evolutionary terms, the human race benefits from nurturing children with a wide range of characteristics. Compared with other species, we have “a much longer immaturity, a much larger relative brain size, and a much greater ability to learn”. Because human babies stay needy for so long, they were often, in our evolutionary past, cared for by multiple members of a community. Gopnik draws on numerous studies to show that children learn best by listening to and observing many different people. We acquire skills by playing and, later, by apprenticeship. It is therefore crazy, she suggests, to create a school system in which play is progressively stifled and in which children are taught science not by doing it but by reading about it and filling in quizzes.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Our job isn't to shape our children’s minds; it’s to let those minds explore all the possibilities that the world allows</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>Gopnik is not the first to have argued for a less instrumental and more playful view of childhood, but her book is still a welcome corrective to the results-driven approach to parenting. Her book makes a fine companion to <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jan/23/review-far-from-the-tree\" title=\"\"><em>Far from the Tree</em> by Andrew Solomon</a>, although she writes with less poetry than Solomon and, for my taste, goes on one digression too many about the wonders of her own grandchildren (“When Augie or Georgie are in the room it’s hard for me to see anybody else”). Augie, her grandson, is “a proven chick magnet” and loves books so much he reads them on the potty. Aged one, he charms the man at the farmers’ market into giving him a cherry and hazelnut biscotti. He tries to imitate his grandfather by using a wooden spoon to dig up mouthfuls of vegan, organic sorbet.</p> <p>To Gopnik, Augie’s sorbet-eating skills are yet more proof that human children are “remarkably effective social learners”, when given the freedom. True, but we could also parse the scene in another way. The problems with how children are raised today cannot all be reduced to parenting. There is also the sheer injustice of a world where some children have biscotti and books and loving grandparents to buy them; and others have none.• To order The Gardener and the Carpenter for £12.29 (RRP £18.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/gardener-and-the-carpenter.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","wordcount":"1346","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-30T00:00:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/5vxv8","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/08f0335f47228d00829dec16956704b363be1d94/0_173_5048_3030/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/scienceandnature","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Science and nature","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/scienceandnature","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/scienceandnature","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"books/series/book-of-the-day","type":"series","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Book of the day","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/series/book-of-the-day","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/book-of-the-day","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webTitle":"Culture","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","type":"tone","webTitle":"Reviews","we